Table 1: employees
+----+-----------+--------+
| id | name      | dept   |
+----+-----------+--------+
| 1  | Ramesh    | IT     |
| 2  | Suresh    | HR     |
| 3  | Mahesh    | IT     |
| 4  | Naresh    | Sales  |
| 5  | Rajesh    | HR     |
| 6  | Kiran     | IT     |
+----+-----------+--------+

Table 2: salaries
+----+------------+--------+
| emp_id | salary | bonus  |
+-------+--------+--------+
| 1     | 50000  | 5000   |
| 2     | 40000  | 4000   |
| 3     | 60000  | 6000   |
| 4     | 45000  | 4500   |
| 5     | 42000  | 4200   |
| 6     | 70000  | 7000   |
+-------+--------+--------+



1Ô∏è‚É£ Employee name and salary
SELECT t1.name, t2.salary
FROM employees AS t1
INNER JOIN salaries AS t2
ON t1.id = t2.id;


‚úÖ Correct

2Ô∏è‚É£ Employee name, department, and bonus
SELECT t1.name, t1.dept, t2.bonus
FROM employees AS t1
INNER JOIN salaries AS t2
ON t1.id = t2.id;


‚úÖ Correct

3Ô∏è‚É£ Employees with salary > 50000 (include all columns)
SELECT *
FROM employees AS t1
INNER JOIN salaries AS t2
ON t1.id = t2.id
WHERE t2.salary > 50000;


‚úÖ Correct

4Ô∏è‚É£ Employees with total salary > 60000 (salary + bonus)

Here‚Äôs how you can add the two columns in SQL:

SELECT t1.name, t1.dept, (t2.salary + t2.bonus) AS total_salary
FROM employees AS t1
INNER JOIN salaries AS t2
ON t1.id = t2.id
WHERE (t2.salary + t2.bonus) > 60000;


üí° t2.salary + t2.bonus calculates total salary on the fly
This is exactly how MNCs expect it

5Ô∏è‚É£ Department-wise total salary
SELECT t1.dept, SUM(t2.salary) AS department_wise_total_salary
FROM employees AS t1
INNER JOIN salaries AS t2
ON t1.id = t2.id
GROUP BY t1.dept;


‚úÖ Correct

6Ô∏è‚É£ HR employees with bonus
SELECT t1.name, t2.bonus
FROM employees AS t1
INNER JOIN salaries AS t2
ON t1.id = t2.id
WHERE t1.dept = 'HR';


‚úÖ Correct

7Ô∏è‚É£ IT employees with salary > 60000
SELECT t1.name, t2.salary, t1.dept
FROM employees AS t1
INNER JOIN salaries AS t2
ON t1.id = t2.id
WHERE t1.dept = 'IT' AND t2.salary > 60000;


‚úÖ Correct

8Ô∏è‚É£ Average salary per department
SELECT t1.dept, AVG(t2.salary) AS avg_salary_per_department
FROM employees AS t1
INNER JOIN salaries AS t2
ON t1.id = t2.id
GROUP BY t1.dept;


‚úÖ Correct

Previous error: AS t1 after AVG was wrong

9Ô∏è‚É£ Employee name and total salary, sorted descending
SELECT t1.name, (t2.salary + t2.bonus) AS total_salary
FROM employees AS t1
INNER JOIN salaries AS t2
ON t1.id = t2.id
ORDER BY total_salary DESC;
